---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "WSJ Stocks Dividend Analysis & History",
  description: "Does the publisher of the Wall Street Journal pay a dividend? We analyze News Corp's (NWSA) exact dividend yield, 5-year payout history, and growth potential.",
  category: "study",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": ["Article", "FAQPage"],
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the ticker symbol for WSJ stocks?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The Wall Street Journal is not a standalone publicly traded company. It is owned by News Corporation, which trades under the ticker symbols NWSA (Class A) and NWS (Class B)."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do WSJ stocks (News Corp) pay a dividend?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, News Corp (NWSA) pays a modest semi-annual dividend. Currently, the dividend yield sits around 0.71%, translating to an annual payout of roughly $0.20 per share."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How often does News Corp pay dividends?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Unlike most US equities that pay quarterly, News Corp pays its dividends semi-annually, typically making distributions in April and October."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Has News Corp increased its dividend recently?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No, News Corp has maintained a flat dividend of $0.20 per share annually ($0.10 semi-annually) for several years, prioritizing reinvestment in digital assets like REA Group over dividend growth."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is NWSA a good dividend stock?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "For pure income investors, NWSA is generally not considered a strong dividend stock due to its low sub-1% yield and lack of payout growth. It is better viewed as a value or sum-of-the-parts play."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/wsj-stocks" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>WSJ Stocks Dividend Analysis & History</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">An inside look at News Corp (NWSA) payouts and yield.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <p>Investors looking for <strong>WSJ stocks</strong> are actually looking for the media conglomerate <strong>News Corporation (NWSA)</strong>. As the publisher of the world's leading financial newspaper, The Wall Street Journal, along with massive digital real estate assets like REA Group, News Corp presents an interesting value proposition. But does this media empire actually pay its shareholders a dividend?</p>

      <h2>Current Dividend Yield and Payout Profile</h2>
      <p>Yes, News Corp (NWSA) does pay a dividend, but it is relatively modest. Furthermore, unlike the vast majority of U.S. equities, News Corp distributes its dividends semi-annually rather than quarterly.</p>

      <div class="stats-grid">
        <div class="stat-card">
          <h3>NWSA Yield</h3>
          <p class="calc-result-value">0.71%</p>
          <span class="badge neutral">Semi-Annual Payout</span>
        </div>
        <div class="stat-card">
          <h3>Trailing P/E Ratio</h3>
          <p class="calc-result-value">72.4</p>
          <span class="badge neutral">Media & Digital Real Estate</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>Currently, NWSA offers a dividend yield of approximately 0.71%. This translates to an annual distribution of exactly $0.20 per share, paid in two installments of $0.10 each (typically in April and October).</p>

      <h2>5-Year Dividend History</h2>
      <p>If you are an investor looking for <a href="/dividend-aristocrats">dividend growth</a>, News Corp is not the stock for you. For the last five years, the company has maintained a stubbornly flat payout schedule.</p>

      <div class="table-container">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Year</th>
              <th>Annual Dividend</th>
              <th>YoY Growth</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>2024</td>
              <td>$0.20</td>
              <td>0.00%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2023</td>
              <td>$0.20</td>
              <td>0.00%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2022</td>
              <td>$0.20</td>
              <td>0.00%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2021</td>
              <td>$0.20</td>
              <td>0.00%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2020</td>
              <td>$0.20</td>
              <td>0.00%</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>Dividend Growth Rate Analysis</h2>
      <p>As the table illustrates, the compound annual growth rate (CAGR) for NWSA's dividend over the past half-decade is exactly zero. Management has explicitly signaled that their primary capital allocation strategy involves reinvesting in their highly profitable Dow Jones segment (which includes WSJ) and scaling their digital real estate services segment, rather than increasing shareholder payouts.</p>

      <h2>Comparison to Category Average</h2>
      <p>When compared to other traditional media and publishing companies, News Corp's 0.71% yield sits firmly on the lower end. However, its business model is far more diversified than a pure-play newspaper company. Because a massive portion of its valuation is derived from its majority stake in Australia's REA Group (a digital real estate juggernaut), investors often value NWSA more like a tech or marketplace stock rather than a high-yield legacy media company.</p>

      <h2>Key Metrics and Fundamentals</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Ticker:</strong> NWSA (Class A) and NWS (Class B voting shares).</li>
        <li><strong>Valuation:</strong> Trades at a seemingly high trailing P/E of 72.4, largely due to accounting amortizations in the publishing segment; its forward P/E and free cash flow yield look much healthier.</li>
        <li><strong>Ex-Dividend Dates:</strong> Generally mid-March and mid-September, with payments hitting accounts roughly a month later.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="calculator-card">
        <h3>WSJ Stocks Dividend Income Calculator</h3>
        <p>Estimate the projected annual income from your NWSA shares based on the flat $0.20/year payout.</p>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="shares">Shares Owned</label>
          <div class="input-wrapper">
            <input type="number" id="shares" value="1000" min="1" step="1">
            <span class="suffix">shares</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="dps">Annual Dividend Per Share ($)</label>
          <div class="input-wrapper">
            <input type="number" id="dps" value="0.20" min="0" step="0.01" readonly style="background: var(--bg-color); opacity: 0.7; cursor: not-allowed;">
            <span class="suffix">/ yr</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="calc-result">
          <span class="calc-result-label">Projected Annual Income</span>
          <div class="calc-result-value" id="projectedIncome">$200.00</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <section class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <details>
          <summary>What is the ticker symbol for WSJ stocks?</summary>
          <p>The Wall Street Journal is not a standalone publicly traded company. It is owned by News Corporation, which trades under the ticker symbols NWSA (Class A) and NWS (Class B).</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Do WSJ stocks (News Corp) pay a dividend?</summary>
          <p>Yes, News Corp (NWSA) pays a modest semi-annual dividend. Currently, the dividend yield sits around 0.71%, translating to an annual payout of roughly $0.20 per share.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>How often does News Corp pay dividends?</summary>
          <p>Unlike most US equities that pay quarterly, News Corp pays its dividends semi-annually, typically making distributions in April and October.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Has News Corp increased its dividend recently?</summary>
          <p>No, News Corp has maintained a flat dividend of $0.20 per share annually ($0.10 semi-annually) for several years, prioritizing reinvestment in digital assets like REA Group over dividend growth.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Is NWSA a good dividend stock?</summary>
          <p>For pure income investors, NWSA is generally not considered a strong dividend stock due to its low sub-1% yield and lack of payout growth. It is better viewed as a value or sum-of-the-parts play.</p>
        </details>
      </section>
    </section>
  </div>
  <script is:inline>
    function initWSJCalculator() {
      const container = document.querySelector('.calculator-card');
      if (!container || container.dataset.initialized === 'true') return;

      const sharesInput = document.getElementById('shares');
      const dpsInput = document.getElementById('dps');
      const projectedIncome = document.getElementById('projectedIncome');

      function updateCalculator() {
        const shares = parseFloat(sharesInput.value) || 0;
        const dps = parseFloat(dpsInput.value) || 0;

        const income = shares * dps;
        projectedIncome.textContent = `$${income.toFixed(2)}`;
      }

      sharesInput.addEventListener('input', updateCalculator);

      container.dataset.initialized = 'true';
    }

    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', initWSJCalculator);
    document.addEventListener('astro:page-load', initWSJCalculator);
  </script>
  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .content-section { margin-top: 2rem; }
    .stats-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0; }
    .stat-card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; text-align: center; }
    .stat-card h3 { font-size: 1.1rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .calc-result-value { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--accent-color); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .badge { display: inline-block; padding: 0.25rem 0.75rem; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 600; border-radius: 9999px; font-family: var(--font-mono); }
    .badge.neutral { background-color: rgba(148, 163, 184, 0.1); color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .table-container { overflow-x: auto; margin: 2rem 0; }
    table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 12px; overflow: hidden; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    th, td { padding: 1rem; text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    th { background-color: rgba(74, 143, 231, 0.05); color: var(--accent-color); font-weight: 600; text-transform: uppercase; font-size: 0.85rem; }
    td { color: var(--text-secondary); font-family: var(--font-mono); }
    tr:last-child td { border-bottom: none; }
    .calculator-card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2.5rem 0; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); }
    .calculator-card h3 { text-align: center; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .calculator-card p { text-align: center; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .input-group { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .input-group label { display: block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600; }
    .input-wrapper { position: relative; display: flex; align-items: center; }
    .input-wrapper input { width: 100%; background: var(--bg-color); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-primary); font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 1.1rem; padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-radius: 8px; }
    .input-wrapper input:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); }
    .suffix { position: absolute; right: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); font-family: var(--font-mono); pointer-events: none; }
    .calc-result { margin-top: 2rem; padding-top: 1.5rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color); text-align: center; }
    .calc-result-label { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.95rem; display: block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .faq-section { margin-top: 3rem; }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1.25rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .faq-section details p { margin-top: 1rem; margin-bottom: 0; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
